Today's #frogmanfriday lesson is about swim buddies. In the SEAL teams your swim buddy is your life. A swim buddy saves your life if you pass out on an underwater demolition mission. They save your life if you get shot in a firefight. A swim buddy is the critical smallest denomination of almost any operation. In the civilian world swim buddies are equally important. They should embody the same virtues of loyalty, love, protection, encouragement, and accomplishment. Here's @heatherbabbz who embodies all the best qualities of a swim buddy. Or maybe she's just admiring our matching fins 🤿. Tag your best swim buddies in the comments below. 📸 @j.kowitz

On this President's day as @potus makes a historic trip to #Ukraine, I wanted to reflect on my own trip to Kiev just last week.

I had not been back to Kiev since the very beginning of the war. At that time we were rescuing people amidst the fighting trapped behind enemy lines. Russians roamed the streets of suburban Kiev, and artillery rained down around us like steel hail. The Kiev that President Biden visits today is vastly different. Restaurants are open. Kids go to school. Movie theaters are open. Except for the occasional missile or drone strike you are sometimes hard pressed to remember there's a war.

The credit for this goes of course the the brave Ukrainian warriors I was privileged enough to fight alongside. But bullets are only half the story. The other half is a series of extraordinary and selfless Americans (and others) who continue to this day bringing aid to the Ukrainian people. Best in class among them is @globalempowermentmission led by the tireless @michaelcapponi and supported by my friend Howard Buffett. 

I've been privileged to work with Michael and GEM since the first days of the war. GEM has built an incredible logistical operation, suppling thousands of tons of food and aid every other week. They have trucks crisscrossing the country to the front lines getting aid in the hands of people who need it the most. I was privileged on this last trip, to be able to deliver some of that aid myself, alongside Michael, directly to those in harms way. just like POTUS renewed the US commitment to supporting Ukraine today; Myself, @GEM, and the @guildfoundation will continue to make herculean efforts to support the people of Ukraine 🇺🇦.

Kaj Larsen is a former NAVY Seal, War Correspondent, and is the Co-Founder of Guild Financial.

The people you surround yourself with have a huge impact on your life, whether you realize it or not. 

If you’re hanging out with negative, lazy, and uninspired people, then you’re likely to become just like them. 

It’s time to wake up and take control of the people in your life!

Stop settling for toxic relationships and start surrounding yourself with people who will lift you up and help you become the best version of yourself. 

Don’t let anyone hold you back or bring you down. 

It’s time to start being intentional about the relationships you build. 

Seek out individuals who inspire, motivate, and challenge you. 

Find people who have achieved what you want to achieve and who embody the qualities that you want to develop. 

And if you have people in your life who are negative, unsupportive, or holding you back, it’s time to cut them loose.

Don’t let anyone drag you down or hold you back from reaching your full potential. 

Take control of the people you surround yourself with and start building a circle of support and positivity. 

You have the power to create the life you want, but it starts with the people you let into your life. 

So choose wisely, and don’t settle for anything less than greatness.

Navy SEAL Hell Week is essentially a test of one’s inner toughness. The grueling physical and mental challenges of this training are designed to push individuals to their limits and beyond, in order to determine if they have what it takes to become a Navy SEAL.

But it’s not just about physical strength or endurance - it’s about mental fortitude and resilience as well. SEALs are required to operate in some of the most challenging and dangerous environments imaginable, often facing life-or-death situations that require split-second decision-making and a willingness to push through pain and discomfort.

In many ways, Hell Week is a microcosm of what it takes to succeed as a SEAL. It’s a crucible that tests every aspect of a person’s character, revealing their strengths and weaknesses in the process. And while not everyone is cut out for this kind of work, those who are willing to embrace the challenge and push themselves to their limits are the ones who ultimately succeed.

So yes, in many ways, Navy SEAL Hell Week is just finding out how tough you are inside. But for those who are willing to dig deep and push through the pain, it can also be the first step on a journey toward becoming one of the most elite warriors on the planet.

SEAL training is a marathon not a sprint. Sometimes the only mechanism for survival is putting one foot in front of the other and just keep going. It's a lot like running a rock underwater for 5 miles. One of the mantras that kept us going during SEAL training (and the @tenthousand rock run) was a poem by William Ernest Henley from 1875 called Invictus. Credit to my swim buddy @mojoluttrell for making this our class inspiration. #sealsaturday 

Out of the night that covers me,
Black as the pit from pole to pole,
I thank whatever gods may be
For my unconquerable soul.

In the fell clutch of circumstance
I have not winced nor cried aloud.
Under the bludgeonings of chance
My head is bloody, but unbowed.

Beyond this place of wrath and tears
Looms but the Horror of the shade,
And yet the menace of the years
Finds and shall find me unafraid.

It matters not how strait the gate,
How charged with punishments the scroll,
I am the master of my fate,
I am the captain of my soul.

This Frogman Friday hits a little different. This is one of the many thousands of Level 4 plate carriers that were delivered by the @guildfoundation to the frontlines of Ukraine. This particular vest was being worn by a member of the 125th Territorial Defense Force who had been mobilized to fight in Bahkmut. His unit was hit during an operation and shrapnel pierced right through a 30 round magazine into his chest. Luckily the plates stopped the projectile saving his life. That's why we do what we do. #savinglives #ukraine #humanitarianwork #veteranshelpingveterans

This #frogmanfriday is about veterans helping veterans and how we can continue to serve even out of uniform.

In March of 2022 The Guild Foundation deployed to #ukraine to conduct Humanitarian Operations. We were one of the first organizations boots on the ground when the war started. The Foundation was able to rescue hundreds of people and supply hundreds of thousands of dolllars of lifesaving medical gear and equipment to the frontlines. We were able to do a lot of good, but there's probably no effort I'm more proud of then Operation Roman. This is a clip about Operation Roman. To see the full story of this courageous young man and to learn how you can help, visit https://theguildfoundation.org/operation-roman

The Guild Foundation has been supporting humanitarian operations in Ukraine. Through our donors’ and partners’ generosity, the Guild Foundation is sponsoring Roman, a 23-year-old Ukrainian Explosive Engineer, to the United States for rehabilitation inpatient care, outpatient care, and lower extremity prostheses. 

For more information about our efforts in Ukraine and to learn about the other mission areas of the foundation please visit TheGuildFoundation.org

This is a helmet I wore overseas for multiple deployments during the early part of my SEAL career. I brought it to Ukraine as a back up helmet when I arrived at the front. On one operation we performed a casualty evacuation of a young American who had volunteered to fight and had been shot while on a mission in Sveredonestk. We successfully evacuated him for recovery in Poland.

A few months later I got a call from another American named Tom who was coming over to join the foreign legion and fight with the Ukrainian Army. He was a friend of the American I had evacuated months earlier and had found my phone number. He explained to me that he had his helmet and body armor taken by TSA when he was boarding the plane for Ukraine. He was basically showing up naked to the fight and asked if I could help.

I gave Tom a spare set of body armor and my backup helmet. Candidly Tom was headed into the belly of the beast, and I was pretty sure I would never see him or my Helmet again.

Just a few days ago I got a message from Tom with this photo. He told me that he had taken a direct hit, and he was sorry but my helmet got a little damaged.

Meeting Tom was one of the many random acts of war that is usually forgotten. Americans who don’t know each other helping each other out on the front line, united with a random purpose to help strangers whose whole lives had just been disrupted by war. Hearing from him, seeing that my helmet which had protected my noggin for so long and had now saved his, was a bright spot in the otherwise bleak landscape of combat. #frogmanfriday #ukraine #slavaukraine🇺🇦

On this Memorial Day I bow my head in honor of my brothers who have paid the ultimate sacrifice.

When I entered the military in 2001, we were enjoying what policy wonks call "the peace dividend." I joined the SEAL community which some people jokingly referred to as a shoot, dive, jump club. I was in first phase of training on  September 11th. We immediately entered a wartime posture. Unbeknownst to me at the time, we would be at war for practically the next two decades. The special operations community would carry a disproportionate share of the burden. I would go on to conduct four deployments in the Global War on Terror, spending the next 13 years of my life in service of the country.

I carried more caskets by the time I was 27 years old than most people do in a lifetime. I still feel the weight of those caskets, but I also feel a heavier burden. I feel a responsibility that my friends, my brothers, did not die in vain. I feel a responsibility that their values of service and sacrifice live on through us and our actions.

The officers of #ironsquad These are my fellow officers from the Korean special forces units. As leaders in the special operations community we have a unique challenge. We have to lead by example, not rank. This is a world where officers have to walk the walk, side by side with the enlisted personnel. If you don't, your career in Special Forces will be short lived.

In fact, SEAL training is unique in warfare qualification selection in that officers and enlisted go through the identical training. This is reflected in our insignia, the gold trident, worn by officers and enlisted alike. In other communities warfare qualification pins for enlisted members are silver, and gold for officers. In the SEAL teams though we all rate gold warfare pins- because we have all have run the same gauntlet together.

This creates a culture that is more horizontal than vertical. Where every man is a leader and follower. An awesome experience to compete with my fellow Korean officers and watch that dynamic play out regardless of the uniform we wear.

This #frogmanfriday is devoted to our #usmc brethren. 248 years ago On November 10, 1775 in a tavern in Philadelphia the Continental Marines were established. To this day the Marine Corps exists under the Department of the Navy. We are sister services, have worked together since the beginning, and continue to fight side by side  in battle to this day.

I was privileged to grow up the son a US Marine, to have deployed with the first Marines Special Operations element, and to call so many Marines my brothers. Chief among them is @realrudyreyes a fearsome fighter and best brother in arms a man could ask for. He defines the essence of a spiritual warrior on a vision quest to improve his life and the life of others. I'm so proud to walk by Rudy's side, swim underwater with him, and take on missions of all kinds. Semper Fi to Rudy and all the other proud Marines out there.
